        <introduction>
            <p>We have noted previously that the instantaneous rate of change of a function <m>z = f(x,y)</m> at the point <m>(x,y) = (x_0,y_0)</m> will depend on the direction in which the independent variables are changing. </p>

            <example xml:id="Ex-Direction_and_rate_of_change_Copy">
            <!-- <title>Direction and Rate of Change</title> -->

                <p>Consider the function <m>f(x,y) = x^2-y^2</m>. The graph of this function is shown below. At <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>, <m>f=0</m>. As we can see by looking at the graph, as we move away from the origin along the positive <m>x</m>-axis the value of <m>f</m> is increasing, i.e. the rate of change of the function will be positive. However, if we move away from the origin along the positive <m>y</m>-axis the value of <m>f</m> is decreasing, i.e. the rate of change of the function will be negative.</p>

                <figure xml:id="Fig-Example_1_Contour_Plot_Copy">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Ex1_Contour_Plot_Fig_1.png" width="70%"/>
                </figure>
            </example>

            <p>In the case that the direction is parallel to the positive x-axis we already know that the slope is given by the partial derivative <m>f_x(x_0,y_0)</m> and in the case that the direction is parallel to the positive <m>y</m>-axis the slope is given by <m>f_y(x_0,y_0)</m>. In this section we will look at the problem of finding the slope of the function if we move away from the point <m>(x,y) = (x_0,y_0)</m> in any direction.</p>

        </introduction>
<!-- =================================================================================================== -->




<!-- =================================================================================================== -->
<!-- Section 1: Directional Derivatives -->
<!-- =================================================================================================== -->
        <section xml:id="Directional-Derivatives">
            <title>Directional Derivatives</title>

            <p>Firstly, note that <m>2D</m> vectors are a convenient way to specify directions in the <m>xy</m>-plane. For example, we could say the slope of the function in the direction of the vector <m>\bm{i} = \langle 1, 0 \rangle</m> is <m>f_x(x_0,y_0)</m> while in the direction of the vector <m>\bm{j} = \langle 0,1 \rangle</m> it is <m>f_y(x_0,y_0)</m>. Thus the problem we are looking at is that of finding the slope of the function at the point <m>(x,y) = (x_0,y_0)</m> in the direction given by some vector <m>\bm{u} = \langle u_1, u_2 \rangle</m>. Mathematically, we would say that we are trying to find the <em>directional derivative</em> of the function <m>f(x,y)</m> at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> in the direction <m>\bm{u}</m>. The notation that we use to denote this directional derivative is <me>D_{\bm{u}}f(x_0,y_0)</me>.</p>

            <p>One way to approach the problem of finding the directional derivative <m>D_{\bm{u}}f(x_0,y_0)</m> is to use the tangent plane to the function at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m>, i.e. <me>L(x,y) = f(x_0,y_0) + f_x (x_0,y_0)(x - x_0) + f_y(x_0,y_0) (y-y_0)</me>.</p>

            <p>Then the slope of the function <m>f(x,y)</m> in the direction of <m>\bm{u}</m> is the slope of <m>L(x,y)</m> in that direction. If <m>\hat{\bm{u}} = \langle u_1, u_2 \rangle</m> is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\bm{u}</m> then the required slope is the amount by which the value of <m>L</m> changes as the independent variables change from <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> to <m>(x_0+u_1,y_0+u_2)</m>, i.e.</p>

            <p><md>
                <mrow>D_u f(x_0,y_0) \amp = L(x_0+u_1, y_0+u_2) - L(x_0,y_0)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \bigg[ f(x_0,y_0) + f_x(x_0,y_0)(x_0+u_1 - x_0) + f_y(x_0,y_0)(y_0+u_2-y_0) \bigg] - f(x_0,y_0)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = f_x(x_0,y_0)u_1 + f_y(x_0,y_0)u_2</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <example xml:id="Ex-Directional_Derivative">
            <!-- <title>Direction and Rate of Change</title> -->

                <p>Consider the function <m>z(x,y) = 5 - \dfrac{x^2+y^2}{2}</m>. Figure 2 shows the graph of this function along with its the tangent plane at <m>(x,y) = (2,1)</m>. Also shown on the diagram are the vectors <m>\bm{u} = \langle 2,2 \rangle</m> and <m>\bm{v} = \langle 2,-1 \rangle</m> drawn in the <m>xy</m>-plane with their tails at the point <m>(x,y) = (2,1)</m>. Then the directional derivative <m>D_{\bm{u}}(z(2,1))</m> will be the slope of the line joining the points <m>(2,1,z(2,1))</m> and <m>(4,3,L(4,3))</m> while the directional derivative <m>D_{\bm{v}}(f(2,1))</m> will be the slope of the line joining the points <m>(2,1,z(2,1))</m> and <m>(4,0,L(4,0))</m>.</p>

                <figure xml:id="Fig-Example_2-Directional-Derivative">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Directional_Derivative_Example.png" width="70%"/>
                </figure>
            </example>

            <p>To summarise:</p>

            <definition>
                <title>Directional Derivative</title>
                <statement><p>The <em>directional derivative</em> of the differentiable function <m>f(x,y)</m> at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> in the direction of the unit vector <m>\hat{\bm{u}} = \langle u_1, u_2 \rangle</m> is given by <me>D_{\bm{u}} f(x_0,y_0) = f_x(x_0,y_0)u_1 + f_y (x_0,y_0)u_2</me>.</p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <example xml:id="Ex-Find_Directional_Derivative">
            <!-- <title>Calculating Partial Derivatives at a Particular Point</title> -->
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the directional derivative of <m>f(x,y) = y\ln(x)</m> at <m>(1,-3)</m> in the direction <m>\bm{u} = \langle -4, 3 \rangle</m>.</p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>For the given function <me>f_x = \dfrac{y}{x} \: \text{ and } \: f_y = \ln(x)</me>. Thus <me>f_x(1,-3) = -3 \: \text{ and } \: f_y(1,-3) = 0</me>. Now the unit vector in the direction of <m>\langle -4,3 \rangle</m> is <me>\hat{\bm{u}} = \left \langle -\dfrac{4}{5}, \dfrac{3}{5} \right \rangle</me>. Thus the required directional derivative is <me>D_\hat{\bm{u}} f(1,-3) = (-3) \left( -\dfrac{4}{5} \right) + (0) \left( \dfrac{3}{5} \right) = \dfrac{12}{5}</me>.</p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <example xml:id="Ex-Find_Directional_Derivative_2">
            <!-- <title>Calculating Partial Derivatives at a Particular Point</title> -->
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the directional derivative of <m>f(x,y) = \sin(x+2y)</m> in the direction of the angle (from the positive <m>x</m>-axis) <m>\theta = \dfrac{3 \pi}{4}</m>.</p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>For the given function <me>f_x = \cos(x+2y) \: \text{ and } \: f_y = 2\cos(x+2y)</me>. Now, the unit vector in the direction of the angle <m>\theta = \dfrac{3 \pi}{4}</m> is <me>\hat{\bm{u}} = \left \langle - \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right \rangle</me>. Thus the required directional derivative is
                        <md>
                            <mrow>D_\hat{\bm{u}} f(x,y) \amp = \cos(x+2y) \left( - \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) + 2\cos(x+2y) \left( \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \cos(x+2y)</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <p>Note that the directional derivative <m>D_\bm{u} f(x_0,y_0)</m> can be expressed in the terms of the scalar product if we use the following definition.</p>

            <definition>
                <title>Gradient Vector</title>
                <statement><p>The vector <me>\nabla f(x_0,y_0) = \langle f_x(x_0,y_0), f_y(x_0,y_0) \rangle</me> is called the <em>gradient vector</em> of <m>f(x,y)</m> at <m>(x_0,y_0)</m>.</p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>With this definition the directional derivative can be written as:
                <md>
                    <mrow>D_\bm{u} f(x_0,y_0) \amp = \langle f_x(x_0,y_0),f_y(x_0,y_0) \cdot \langle u_1, u_2 \rangle</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \nabla f(x_0,y_0) \cdot \hat{\bm{u}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <example xml:id="Ex-Find_Gradient_Vector">
            <!-- <title>Calculating Partial Derivatives at a Particular Point</title> -->
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the gradient vector for the function <m>f(x,y) = e^{-x} \sin(y)</m>. Hence find <m>\nabla f(0,\pi/3)</m> and the directional derivative in the direction of the origin.</p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>For the given function <me>f_x = -e^{-x} \sin(y) \: \text{ and } \: f_y = e^{-x}\cos(y)</me>, and so the gradient vector is <me>\nabla f = \left \langle -e^{-x}\sin(y), e^{-x}\cos(y) \right \rangle</me>. Thus <me>\nabla f(0, \pi/3) = \left \langle -e^0 \sin \left( \dfrac{\pi}{3} \right), e^0 \cos \left( \dfrac{\pi}{3} \right) \right \rangle = \left \langle - \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} , \dfrac{1}{2} \right \rangle</me>. Now, the unit vector in the direction of the origin from the point <m>\left( 0, \dfrac{\pi}{3} \right)</m> is <me>\hat{\bm{u}} = \langle 0, -1 \rangle</me>. Thus the required directional derivative is <me>D_{\hat{\bm{u}}} f \left( 0, \dfrac{\pi}{3} \right) = \left \langle -\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} , \dfrac{1}{2} \right \rangle \cdot \langle 0, -1 \rangle = - \dfrac{1}{2}</me>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>


            <p>The gradient vector has some interesting facts associated with it. Note in the following we are assuming that <m>\nabla f \neq \langle 0, 0 \rangle</m>.</p>

            <p><ol label="1">

                <li>
                    <p><m>\nabla f</m> points in the direction in which the directional derivative takes on its largest value. To see this, note that
                    <md>
                        <mrow>D_{\bm{u}} f(x,y) \amp = \nabla f(x,y) \cdot \hat{\bm{u}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \| \nabla f \| \| \hat{\bm{u}} \| \cos(\theta)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \| \nabla f \| \cos(\theta)</mrow>
                    </md>
                    At a given point <m>\| \nabla f \|</m> is fixed and so the largest value of <m>D_{\bm{u}} f(x,y)</m> will occur when <m>\cos(\theta) = 1</m>, i.e. when <m>\theta = 0</m> or put another way, when <m>\hat{\bm{u}}</m> is parallel to <m>\nabla f</m>. We can also see from this that the largest value that the directional derivative can take is <m>\| \nabla f \|</m>.</p>

                    <p>Similarly, the directional derivative takes on its smallest value in the direction of <m>-\nabla f</m> and has value <m>- \| \nabla f \|</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p><m>\nabla f(x_0,y_0)</m> is orthogonal (i.e. at right angles) to the level curve passing through <m>(x_0,y_0)</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>For the function <m>z = f(x,y)</m> the level curve passing through the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> is given <me>f(x,y) = f(x_0,y_0)</me>. Now, as shown in Figure <xref ref= "Fig_tangent_vector"/>, a vector parallel to the tangent to this curve at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> will be <m> \left \langle 1, \dfrac{dy}{dx} \right \rangle</m>.
                    </p>

                    <figure xml:id="Fig_tangent_vector">
                        <caption></caption>
                        <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Fig3_tangent_vector.png" width="70%"/>
                    </figure>

                    <p>Thus a vector normal to the curve at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> will be <m>\left \langle \dfrac{f_x(x_0,y_0)}{f_y(x_0,y_0)}, 1 \right \rangle</m>, which is parallel to <m>\nabla f(x_0,y_0)</m>. </p>

                    <p>Notice that since <m>\nabla f(x_0,y_0)</m> is orthogonal to the level curve passing through the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> and that <m>\nabla f (x_0,y_0)</m> is the direction in which the directional derivative takes on its largest value, the <q>path of steepest ascent</q> on any surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> is always at right angles to its contours. See the following diagram for an attempt to show this.</p>

                    <figure xml:id="Fig_Contour_Plot">
                        <caption></caption>
                        <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Fig4_Contour_Plot.png" width="70%"/>
                    </figure>
                </li>

            </ol></p>


            <example xml:id="Ex-Find_Max_Min_Directional_Derivative">
                <statement>
                    <p>For the function <m>f(x,y) = x^2y^3-3x</m> find the directions in which the directional derivative at the point <m>(-2,4)</m> is maximised, minimised and <m>0</m>.</p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>For the given function <me>f_x = 2xy^3-3 \: \text{ and } \: f_y = 3x^2y^2</me>, and so <me>\nabla f(-2,4) = \langle -259,192 \rangle</me>. Thus the directional derivative, <m>D_{\hat{\bm{u}}} f(-2,4)</m>, will be maximised in the direction <me>\bm{u} = \nabla f(-2,4) = \langle -259, 192 \rangle</me> and minimised in the direction <me>\bm{u} = -\nabla f(-2,4) = \langle 259, -192 \rangle</me>. Finally <m>D_{\hat{\bm{u}}} f(-2,4)</m> will be <m>0</m> when
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\nabla f(-2,4) \cdot \bm{u} \amp = 0</mrow>
                        <mrow>-259u_1 + 192u_2 \amp = 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                    i.e. when <me>\bm{u} = \langle 192, 259 \rangle</me> or some scalar multiple of this.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>


            <example xml:id="Ex-Find_lvlcurve_tanline_gradvec">
                <statement>
                    <p>For the function <m>f(x,y) = x^2-y</m> find the level curve, the tangent line and the gradient vector at the point <m>(-3,1)</m>.</p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>Since <m>f(-3,1)=8</m> the level curve through the point <m>(-3,1)</m> is <m>x^2-y=8</m> or <m>y=x^2-8</m>. We can find the equation of the tangent by standard calculus to obtain <me>y=-6x-17</me>. Next, the gradient vector is <me>\nabla f(-3,1) = \langle f_x(-3,1), f_y(-3,1) \rangle = \langle -6, -1 \rangle</me>. As can be seen in the diagram below, the gradient vector is orthogonal to the level curve.
                    </p>

                    <figure xml:id="Fig_gradvec_orthogonal_levelcurve">
                        <caption></caption>
                        <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Fig5_gradvec_orthogonal_levelcurve.png" width="70%"/>
                    </figure>
                </solution>
            </example>


            <example xml:id="Ex-Hill_Climbing">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Suppose you are climbing a hill whose shape is given by the equation <me>z = 1000-0.01x^2 - 0.02y^2</me> and you are standing at the point with coordinates <m>(60,100,764)</m>.
                        <p><ol label="a">
                            <li>In which direction should you proceed initially in order to be ascending most rapidly?</li>
                            <li>If you climb in that direction, at what angle to the horizontal will you be climbing initially?</li>
                        </ol></p>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>Since we want to travel on the path of steepest ascent we will want to head in the direction of <m>\nabla f(60,100)</m>. Now <me>\nabla f(x,y) = \langle -0.02x, -0.04y \rangle</me> and hence <me>\nabla f (60,100) = \langle-1.2,-4 \rangle</me>.</li>
                        <li>In this direction we know that <me>D_{\hat{\bm{u}}} f(60,100) = \| \nabla f(60,100) \| \simeq 4.17</me>. Thus the angle, <m>\theta</m>, to the horizontal will be <me>\theta = \tan^{-1} (4.17) \simeq 1.33^{c}</me>.</li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </example>


            <exercises>
            <title>Example Tasks</title>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the directional derivative for <m>f(x,y) = (x-2y)^2 + 5x^2</m> at the point <m>(-3,1)</m> in the direction of the point <m>(1,4)</m>.</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the maximum value of the rate of change of <m>h(s,t) = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{s^2+t^2}}</m> at <m>(3,4)</m>.</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>For the curve <m>e^x \ln (y) - xy = 0</m> use the gradient vector of a two variable function to find the tangent line and the normal line at the point <m>(2,e^2)</m>.</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>For the following contour plot for some unspecified function of two variables estimate the sign of the directional derivatives at:</p>

                    <figure xml:id="ET_Contour_Plot">
                        <caption></caption>
                        <image source="./Calculus/Images/6/Example-Task-4_Contour_Plot.png" width="70%"/>
                    </figure>

                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>The point <m>A</m> and in the direction of <m>\bm{u} = \langle 1,2 \rangle</m>.</li>
                        <li>The point <m>B</m> and in the direction of <m>\bm{w} = \langle -1,-1 \rangle</m>.</li>
                        <li>The point <m>A</m> and in the direction of the origin.</li>
                        <li>The point <m>B</m> and in the direction of the origin.</li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>

        </exercises>


